SIMPLE: weight
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Weight
<hw>Weight</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>weght</ets>,
<ets>wight</ets>, AS. <ets>gewiht</ets>; akin to D. <ets>gewigt</ets>,
G. <ets>gewicht</ets>, Icel. <ets>v⟦ae⟧tt</ets>, Sw. <ets>vigt</ets>,
Dan. <ets>v⟦ae⟧gt</ets>. See <er>Weigh</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality of being heavy; that property of bodies
by which they tend toward the center of the earth; the effect of
gravitative force, especially when expressed in certain units or
standards, as pounds, grams, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Weight</xex> differs from <xex>gravity</xex> in
being the effect of gravity, or the downward pressure of a body under
the influence of gravity; hence, it constitutes a measure of the force
of gravity, and being the resultant of all the forces exerted by gravity
upon the different particles of the body, it is proportional to the
quantity of matter in the body.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The quantity of heaviness; comparative tendency to
the center of the earth; the quantity of matter as estimated by the
balance, or expressed numerically with reference to some standard unit;
<as>as, a mass of stone having the <ex>weight</ex> of five hundred
pounds</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For sorrow, like a heavy-hanging bell,⟦br⟧
Once set on ringing, with his own <qex>weight</qex> goes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Hence, pressure; burden; <as>as, the <ex>weight</ex>
of care or business</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>weight</xex> of this
said time.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>For the public all this <qex>weight</qex> he bears.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] who singly bore the world's sad <qex>weight</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Importance; power; influence; efficacy; consequence;
moment; impressiveness; <as>as, a consideration of vast
<ex>weight</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In such a point of <qex>weight</qex>, so near mine honor.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A scale, or graduated standard, of heaviness; a mode
of estimating weight; <as>as, avoirdupois <ex>weight</ex>; troy
<ex>weight</ex>; apothecaries' <ex>weight</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A ponderous mass; something heavy; <as>as, a clock
<ex>weight</ex>; a paper <ex>weight</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man leapeth better with <qex>weights</qex> in his hands.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A definite mass of iron, lead, brass, or other
metal, to be used for ascertaining the weight of other bodies; <as>as,
an ounce <ex>weight</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>The resistance against which a
machine acts, as opposed to the power which moves it.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Atomic weight</b></col>. <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>See under
<er>Atomic</er>, and cf. <er>Element</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Dead
weight</b></col>, <col><b>Feather weight</b></col>, <col><b>Heavy
weight</b></col>, <col><b>Light weight</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See
under <er>Dead</er>, <er>Feather</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Weight of
observation</b></col> <fld>(Astron. & Physics)</fld>, <cd>a number
expressing the most probable relative value of each observation in
determining the result of a series of observations of the same
kind.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Ponderousness; gravity; heaviness; pressure;
burden; load; importance; power; influence; efficacy; consequence;
moment; impressiveness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weight</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Weight
<hw>Weight</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Weighted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Weighting</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To load with a weight or weights; to load down; to
make heavy; to attach weights to; <as>as, to <ex>weight</ex> a horse or
a jockey at a race; to <ex>weight</ex> a whip handle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The arrows of satire, . . . <qex>weighted</qex> with sense.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron. & Physics)</fld> <def>To assign a weight
to; to express by a number the probable accuracy of, as an observation.
See <cref>Weight of observations</cref>, under
<er>Weight</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Dyeing)</fld> <def>To load (fabrics) as with
barite, to increase the weight, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>to assign a numerical value
expressing relative importance to (a measurement), to be multiplied by
the value of the measurement in determining averages or other aggregate
quantities; <as>as, they <ex>weighted</ex> part one of the test twice as
heavily as part 2</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1640 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weightily</ent>⟦br⟧
